snippet.textDisplay: As a dog trainer, just have to say you should NEVER feel bad for trying to find ways to make things safer for your pups. No one should be shamed for researching and seeing what your dogs are comfortable with. All dogs are different! But, as a tip for next time- anytime you’re introducing something new and potentially overwhelming for your dogs- take it slow. In this situation, you want to get them used to the harnesses completely first. Start in the house, have treats to reward them anytime they do relax wearing the harnesses. It should probably be a multi day process depending on the dog. Even when you start driving, only go a short distance, and when you’re driving make sure you’re rewarding for anytime they’re actually calm in the harness. Make sure you’re advocating for your dogs and give them as much time as they need! Love your channel, Jenna!

No one should be shamed for researching and seeing what your dogs are comfortable with. All dogs are different! But, as a tip for next time- anytime you’re introducing something new and potentially overwhelming for your dogs- take it slow. In this situation, you want to get them used to the harnesses completely first. Start in the house, have treats to reward them anytime they do relax wearing the harnesses. It should probably be a multi day process depending on the dog. Even when you start driving, only go a short distance, and when you’re driving make sure you’re rewarding for anytime they’re actually calm in the harness. Make sure you’re advocating for your dogs and give them as much time as they need! Love your channel, Jenna!
